post_text:
I'm sure you have heard by now that the Council of the Michigan High School Athletic Association today announced it will move the 2020 Fall football season to Spring 2021. This is a difficult day for our Football Players and Cheerleaders who have worked very hard over the summer to stay in shape and have had a great week/two weeks of practice. We will be receiving further guidelines from MHSAA on Wednesday regarding allowed fall coach-player workouts as well as concepts for the spring football season dates, format and playoffs. The coaching staff and I are committed to helping our young athletes through this time and finding a way to make Spring Football the best experience we can for our athletes. As I receive more information, I will pass it on to the coaches and communicate through the BRH Facebook Page.

If you would like to read the MHSAA announcement, here is the link: https://www.mhsaa.com/News/Press-Releases/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/9189/MHSAA-Announces-Football-to-Move-to-Spring-Season-for-2020-21

Jeanne Lippens, Athletic Director

The Little Cedar River Conference (BR-H, Carney, North Central, Holy Name, and Stephenson) met today via zoom and the consensus was to reschedule the Girls Junior High Basketball season to the Spring. We will be meeting again later in the fall to work out logistics and schedules. No decision has been made yet for Boys JH Basketball.

We are posting this on the BRH Facebook page so that our student athletes and parents can see the information as soon as possible because the other schools are also alerting their teams.

As more information becomes available, I will be sure to pass it on.

Jeanne Lippens
Athletic Director

Information on Dual Enrollment:

Fall Semester
Bay College Fall semester is scheduled to begin August 17, and finish November 25. Fall registration is open! Contact your high school or Bay’s Dual Enrollment Coordinator at rogersa@baycollege.edu to get registered. College Textbooks will be at BR-H on the 13th.

Blackboard
All classes are built in Blackboard. Refer to the Bay College Blackboard Quick Start Guide for Students to learn the basics of Blackboard, accessing courses, and online learning.

IT and Online Support
For any questions or support utilizing our online system, please contact our Online Learning Department at onlinehelp@baycollege.edu. For any technical support please contact our IT department at ithelp@baycollege.edu or call 906-217-4025.

Along with BR-H, throughout the state, educators are preparing as a state and as 831 local education agencies (LEAs) and 56 intermediate school districts for a return to school. We truly can't wait to see our kids again.

As the Superintendent and K-12 Principal of a small public school in the Upper Peninsula of Michigan my world drastically changed late on the night of Thursday, March 12th. Around 11:00 p.m., Governor Whitmer declared that due to COVID-19 all school buildings in Michigan would be closing beginning on Monday, March 16th. This eleventh hour declaration put our world into a frenzy. Teachers spent much of the day on Friday the 13th putting together packets for what we thought would be an extended spring break. On March 17th, schools were told to cease all student activities including coursework and enrichment activities since we could not guarantee that all students have access to… More

post_text: The Michigan Department of Health and Human Services has recently announced additional services available through the Pandemic EPT Program. This program works directly with Michigan's Food and Nutrition Program to determine eligibility status. Our elementary school (K-6th grade) is an eligible CEP (Community Eligibility Provision) school and therefore, we anticipate all K-6th grade students will qualify. Students in grades 7 - 12 that qualify for free and reduced lunch will also qualify for these additional supports. We are waiting for additional guidance from DHHS regarding eligibility. This is not a school district program and therefore, you will not receive anything from the school; however, you should receive a letter from DHHS if your family qualifies. Please refer to the information posted in the attachment for specific details.

With the conventional school year being cancelled for now & turning to an online learning format -the 7th-12th grade yearbook will definitely look different this year.
I am reaching out to the Bark River families & asking them to submit pictures of their 7-12th grade students as they finish the remainder of this school year-Pictures of students working on schoolwork, working at home, creating art, practicing their favorite sport, making dinner-pictures of what life is for each of them now. If you have pictures to submit over the next 9 weeks, please email them to tstenberg@brhschools.org
-if you don’t have access to email, please pm me & I’ll send you my phone number.
Thank you so much & please share😃👍🏻
Terra Bennett Stenberg

post_text:
Dear Parents/Guardians,

Over the past several days, requests from various health care organizations have circulated throughout our surrounding communities for disinfectant wipes, soaps, and sanitizing lotions. We have been very fortunate to have collected numerous donations of these items from parents and teachers throughout the year. Our community has given so much to our school and we want to return the favor by providing these items to our health care professionals working tirelessly to keep our community safe. We know that when parents donate items to their school, it is intended to be used in the classrooms; however, these are unusual times and we want to help make a difference. We want to give a shout out to our parents and teachers, for the generous donations throughout the years. We are proud to be able to 're-donate' these items to our local Fire, EMS, and Public Safety workers. We are stronger together!

Go Broncos!--
Jason Lockwood, Ed.S
Superintendent - Bark River-Harris
906-466-9981 ext 116

Bark River Harris Library
March 15 at 7:31 PM ·

Tomorrow evening at 7:00 est, I’ll be doing a live story time on our BRH Library page. Unfortunately due to copyright laws, the video can only be shown while live and I cannot post the video to be played at a later time. I’ve never done this before, so tomorrow will be a trial run. We’ll see how it goes and hopefully, if I have enough viewers, I’ll set up other times during the week.
Reading to the students at BRH is my favorite part of my job and I want to continue reading aloud to the students and any other kids who want to watch! Join me on Facebook tomorrow evening!

post_text:
Dear Parents/Guardians,

The District has brought in additional support today to provide your child's teacher with the necessary time to prepare materials that will be sent home in your student's backpacks. We will not introduce any new content or standards, but rather want our students to review regularly. We will send home library books for our elementary students and encourage families to read together every day. We are loading our ipads with educational resources and assignments for our junior high and high school students, as well as sending home material for our older students to work on. Please make sure to check with your children regarding their educational material that is being sent home today. If you have any questions about the material being sent home from your classroom teacher, please feel free to email them during this three week period.

post_text: BRH would like to acknowledge Mrs. Wells’ as this months Living the Mission winner. Mrs. Wells noticed a national news article about Major Bill White. Major White is 104 years old and the last remaining WWII marine veteran in the United States. His wish was to receive as many valentines as possible this year for the holiday that celebrates love. Mrs. Wells’ class quickly went to work creating wonderful hand made valentines for Mr. White. They filled them with their hand prints, lots of love, and they also thanked him for his service to our country. We hope you all have a very Happy Valentine’s Day!

post_text: Imagine if you will, a huge gymnasium filled with roudy robotics enthusiasts cheering for each other. A team from the lower peninsula chants "FORTY-NINE", followed by a loud reply from upper peninsula students -"SEVENTY"! This type of interaction is not unusual, in fact, it is the norm at robotics competitions. It is that time again as BRH TEAM 4970 gears up for another run at the state tournament. We can't wait to see what this season will bring. We want to thank all past and present sponsors, as these events take an extraordinarily large amount of support to pull off. GOOD LUCK 4970!

We can't wait to see what this season will bring. We want to thank all past and present sponsors, as these events take an extraordinarily large amount of support to pull off. GOOD LUCK 4970!

Congratulations to Mrs. Nancy Prica for winning this months mission challenge!
“For the past three years, I have asked my former physics students to come in and talk to my chemistry and physics classes. Most of my students in these two classes will eventually be moving on into a college program; many of those students will then be graduating from a four year program.
My former students come in and talk about their college experiences during their Christmas break. Some topics they will talk about are what students should be doing to prepare to go to college, what to expect when they are actually at college, what will need to be done to transfer from Bay to a four year program, and what… More

Dear PTO and All Our BR- H Family,

I hope everyone enjoyed their Christmas break and are heading into the new year healthy and happy.

Dixie and I want to send out a very big thank you to the PTO and all the BR-H family for helping us with Dixie’s medical bills. The money was greatly appreciated. Dixie is much more careful when she is heading out of the house to "chase" things. Her vet Dr. Kurt said she has made pretty much a full recovery from her injury and today when I put her collar on to come to school she pranced out to the car. She was eager to get back into the normal routine. She LOVES her work at school!

Thank You Again

Dixie and Mrs. Hood

shared_text:
Connie Wells is with Kristy Maxon-Erickson and 3 others.
December 7, 2019 at 4:43 PM ·

Another successful Upper Peninsula Jr. High Quiz Tournament is in the books. It takes a village of volunteers to make this great event happen. A special thanks to all the people who volunteered to moderate, judge, run the concession stand and carry match results to our main office. A huge THANK YOU to the staff of North Menominee County Community Schools and the UPCEA for heading up this event for the 37th year.
Bark River-Harris School has been honored to host this event for the 10th year in a row. We love celebrating the academic success of our Upper Peninsula youth!
A big congratulations to Calumet. They are the 2019 tournament champions!

post_text: Junior High students from Mrs. Norkoli's Project-Based Learning class celebrated Giving Tuesday this year by taking a class trip to Walmart where they purchased Christmas gifts for seven children off of the Angel Tree at the Delta Plaza Mall. The students raised the money earlier last month by selling baked goods to their peers at an International Dessert Faire. The PBL students first spent time learning all about several other countries and then presented their findings in the form of a faire where fellow students were able to both learn something new as well as purchase some fun cultural treats. This trip to support local children at Christmas was the culmination of their project, and the students enjoyed having the opportunity to give back to the local community.
